The FTIR spectra of intact CMC, GQDs, and CMC/GQDs nanocomposite film including 45% GQDs are presented in Fig. 1
                        e. In the CMC FTIR spectrum, there is a broad peak around 3440 cm−1 that is associated with hydroxyl groups and hydrogen bonding available in the CMC. The appeared band around 1615 and 1517 cm−1 are related to the carboxylate groups (asymmetric and symmetric stretching vibrations). The peak detected at 2920 cm−1 is related to the stretching of the CH bands. The peak around 1250 cm−1 is related to the stretching of the CO on CMC backbone. CMC/GQDs FTIR spectrum showed a peak around 1712 cm−1. This peak is not visible in the FTIR spectra of pure GQDs and CMC. This band could be related to the stretching of CO groups of the ester groups [R1–C(O)O–R2] created during the crosslinking process. It is proved that at the elevated temperatures, the polyfunctional carboxylic acids like citric acid cross-link cellulosic materials via esterification. It is proposed that carboxylate groups of polyfunctional acids will dehydrate leading to cyclic anhydride. This cyclic anhydride reacts with hydroxyl group of a cellulose chain leading to an ester linkage. Another cyclic anhydride group can be produced through dehydration of other non-reacted carboxylic groups, allowing the attachment of another cellulose chain [52–54]. The carboxylic acid groups available on the GQDs surface can be used for crosslinking of CMC as a polyfunctional acid (Fig. 2

                        ).
